British Airways and Virgin Atlantic Airways were among long-haul carriers planning to resume normal service to Hong Kong as crowds of black-clad protesters who closed the airport began to thin out. The UK carriers said services due to depart London on Monday night and take about 12 hours to fly to Hong Kong should operate according to schedule. Deutsche Lufthansa took a more cautious approach and said there will be no trips to the Chinese territory until Tuesday at the earliest. Read: Hong Kong violence intensifies during 10th weekend of protests Authorities at Chek Lap Kok airport said they intend to resume operations by 6 am local time on Tuesday. Hereâ€™s how long-haul carriers in Europe and the US are responding to the situation: